## 2. Terrestrial SoOP in/around Danish waters

### 2.1 DVB-T2 (Denmark / southern Sweden / northern Germany)

**[VERIFIED]** Denmark DTT is **DVB-T2** (transition completed; five national multiplexes as of 2025 Wikipedia summary; MUX1 free-to-air DIGI-TV (DR/TV 2); MUX2–5 Boxer pay).  
Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital_terrestrial_television (Denmark section; access 2026-07-22)

**[VERIFIED]** DVB-T2 supports **SFN** operation; SFN requires tight time synchronization of all transmitters (industry literature: typically GPS/GNSS receivers at sites, or network/PTP alternatives for resilience).  
Sources:  
- https://wsts.atis.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/WSTS-Magnus_v2.pdf (access 2026-07-22)  
- https://www.vidi.eu/download_file/147/0 (SFN sync white paper; GPS as traditional method; access 2026-07-22)

**[ASSUMED]** Danish / southern Swedish / northern German DVB-T2 SFNs are **GNSS-disciplined in the default industry architecture**. No public operator statement (DR / Digi-TV / Boxer / Teracom-class) confirming Denmark-specific GNSS vs PTP-only architecture was found this session. For SoOP usability this matters: if transmitters are GNSS-held, transmitter phase/time may degrade under regional GNSS spoofing/jamming (relevant given Baltic GNSS interference reports).

**[ASSUMED for Danish waters]** Dense DVB-T2 coverage is strong **nearshore / straits / landward approaches**; open North Sea / deep Kattegat range depends on ERP and geometry — treat as coastal SoOP candidate, not basin-wide.

### 2.2 R-Mode Baltic status (2026)

**[VERIFIED]** R-Mode Baltic began as the world’s first large-scale R-Mode **testbed** (not a certified SOLAS-grade operational navigation service). Roughly **eight transmitters** spanning ~**800 km Heligoland–Stockholm** (Germany–Poland–Sweden corridor).  
Source: DLR (24 Mar 2025): https://www.dlr.de/en/latest/news/2025/towards-standardisationsatellite-independent-navigation-in-the-baltic-sea (access 2026-07-22)

**[VERIFIED]** **ORMOBASS** (Operational R-Mode Baltic Sea System) expands the test area toward **Sweden–Finland–Estonia**. IALA Guideline **1187** (medium-wave R-Mode signal characteristics) available early 2025. DLR states goal to develop essential MF and VHF R-Mode functions by **2026** for maritime authorities; **“From early 2026, the standardised signals will be available in the area between Germany, Finland and Estonia.”**  
Same DLR source; project page: https://interreg-baltic.eu/project/ormobass/ (access 2026-07-22)

**[VERIFIED]** ResearchGate figure caption (testbed as of 3 Mar 2025): MF R-Mode stations active; **VHF R-Mode transmitters “currently not available in the Baltic but… activated in the near future.”**  
Source: https://www.researchgate.net/figure/R-Mode-Baltic-Sea-testbed-as-of-3-March-2025-The-green-triangles-represent-the-MF-R-Mode_fig1_401151122 (access 2026-07-22)

**Status summary (as of this research date):**

| Aspect | Assessment | Label |
|---|---|---|
| Full operational (SOLAS-grade) R-Mode service | **No** — still project/testbed + standardisation rollout | VERIFIED (DLR language: test field, standardisation, authorities for operation) |
| Usable test signals MF | **Yes** in established SW Baltic corridor; expansion east/north 2025–2026 | VERIFIED |
| Coverage of **Danish waters / Danish straits** | **Partial / edge of original Heligoland–Stockholm corridor**; not Denmark-centric network | ASSUMED geometry from DLR map description — confirm station list with DLR/WSV/SMA before planning |
| Receiver ecosystem | Prototype / research receivers (project partners: Alberding, NavSim, Kongsberg Discovery/Seatex, etc.) | VERIFIED partner list on DLR page |

### 2.3 Cellular (LTE/5G) offshore viability

**[VERIFIED]** **North Sea:** Tampnet operates large offshore **4G/5G LTE** footprint (~**300,000 km²** cited across UK, Danish, and Norwegian shelves); roaming products for vessels; private 5G deployments on platforms/rigs.  
Sources:  
- https://www.offshore-energy.biz/tampnet-secures-roam-free-mobile-coverage-for-north-sea-assets/ (access 2026-07-22)  
- https://www.tampnet.com/roaming-north-sea (access 2026-07-22)

**[VERIFIED]** Generic maritime LTE range from **coastal towers** is typically tens of km (vendor/marketing claims up to ~50–70 km with high-gain antennas; standard towers often less). Beyond that, industrial offshore networks or satellite fill gaps.  
Source example: https://weconnect.one/blogs/how-far-offshore-does-4g-work-long-distance-maritime-internet-explained/ (access 2026-07-22)

**[ASSUMED for Danish waters / straits]**  
- **Straits and nearshore (Øresund, Belts, coastal Kattegat):** public Danish/Swedish/German LTE/5G generally viable as SoOP or data backhaul with marine antennas.  
- **Open North Sea (DK shelf):** viable where Tampnet / coastal overlap exists; not continuous for pure public MNO.  
- **Central Baltic / far from coast:** poor for continuous public cellular SoOP; experiments (e.g. Baltic ship-as-base-station demos) are not production coverage.

**SoOP note:** cellular ranging/ToA requires operator cooperation or opportunistic research methods; **coverage ≠ usable timing reference**. Treat cellular as **availability/backhaul** first, PNT SoOP second.

### 2.4 eLoran status in the region

**[VERIFIED]** European legacy Loran largely shut down ~2015; **UK Anthorn** remains an operational eLoran-capable site used for **timing** distribution research/service.  
Sources:  
- ESA NAVISP final presentation note: “one operational eLoran station in Anthorn, UK” — https://navisp.esa.int/news/article/Final%20Presentation%20of%20UK%20Time%20Distribution%20%28NAVISP%20EL3-017%29 (access 2026-07-22)  
- RIN event text on UK maintaining Anthorn while rest of Europe shut down infrastructure (access via search summary 2026-07-22)

**[VERIFIED]** UK government (Nov 2025) announced **£71 million** to begin a **UK National eLoran programme** as part of resilient PNT; earlier **UK–France** PNT/eLoran cooperation messaging (2025).  
Sources:  
- https://www.gov.uk/government/news/landmark-government-investment-to-safeguard-the-essential-signals-we-all-rely-on (access 2026-07-22)  
- https://insidegnss.com/uk-and-france-renew-ties-resilient-pnt-eloran-a-key-part/ (access 2026-07-22)

**[VERIFIED]** No operational multi-station eLoran **navigation** chain covering the **Baltic / Danish straits** was found as of 2026-07-22. Baltic/North Sea states’ Jan 2026 GNSS-interference letter stresses need for alternatives but does not declare eLoran operational there.  
Source: https://valtioneuvosto.fi/en/-/1410829/itameren-ja-pohjanmeren-rantavaltiot-gnss-hairinta-on-lisannyt-merenkulun-turvallisuusriskeja-1 (access 2026-07-22)

**Assessment for Danish waters:** eLoran is a **strategic/UK-led rebuild**, not a currently usable regional maritime PNT layer for Denmark in 2026.

