## 3. Regulatory — manned experimental autopilot / semi-autonomous in Danish waters

**Not legal advice.** Contact authorities for binding interpretation.

### 3.1 Danish authorities & permits

**[VERIFIED]** DMA invites contact to designate test areas and issue permits for new technology testing in Danish waters; framework depends on the specific activity. Contact: **mrj@dma.dk**, +45 72 19 60 00.  
Source: https://www.dma.dk/growth-and-framework-conditions/maritime-digitalization/guidelines-for-testing-maritime-technologies (access 2026-07-22)

**[VERIFIED]** For **remote / autonomous maritime sea drones and autonomous vessels**, DMA guideline “Approval process for Remote Operation of Maritime Sea Drones and Autonomous Vessels in Danish Waters”:

1. Contact DMA **Regulatory Future Lab**: **futurelab@dma.dk** (early engagement recommended).  
2. Formal application via DMA portal for navigation with autonomous vessels/drones (wireless control).  
3. Applications to **DEMA** (Safety of Navigation, National Waters) **≥ 4 weeks** before planned operation.  
4. DMA assesses construction, equipment, operational aspects; DEMA issues final permission if risk assessment shows safe operation consistent with international regulation.  
5. Required: detailed risk assessment (safety of voyage; impact on freedom of navigation of others), operational/technical package (area, traffic, warnings/notice to mariners, support vessels, route, UNCLOS compliance, seaworthiness measures); CONOPS if not already provided.  
6. Additional permits may apply (e.g. Danish Geodata Agency for maritime survey activity).

Source: DMA PDF https://www.dma.dk/Media/638995644980251670/Guideline%20-%20Approval%20process%20for%20Remote%20Operation%20of%20Maritime%20Sea%20Drones.pdf (access 2026-07-22)

**[ASSUMED]** A **manned** vessel with experimental autopilot / semi-autonomy is still “new technology” testing if it departs from conventional manning/watchkeeping assumptions — engage Future Lab early. Pure software logging of PNT with conventional bridge watch may need less process than control authority transfer; DMA decides case-by-case (**not verified as a bright-line rule**).

**[VERIFIED]** DMA references **IMO MSC.1/Circ.1604** Interim Guidelines for MASS Trials.  
Source: DMA testing guidelines page (access 2026-07-22); IMO circular PDF linked from that page.

### 3.2 Sandbox / test-area schemes

**[VERIFIED]** Denmark positions itself as open to experiments and will **“establish the framework for the test area and issue a permit”** based on enquiry — not a single fixed geographic sandbox only, but **activity-specific** test areas. Examples of ongoing test activities are published on DMA site.  
Source: https://www.dma.dk/growth-and-framework-conditions/maritime-digitalization/guidelines-for-testing-maritime-technologies (access 2026-07-22)

### 3.3 COLREGs implications for a manned test platform

**[VERIFIED]** COLREGs **Rule 5** requires every vessel to maintain a proper look-out by sight and hearing and all available means.  
Source: standard COLREGs text e.g. https://ecolregs.com/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&layout=item&id=48&Itemid=505&lang=en (access 2026-07-22)

**[ASSUMED / industry consensus, not a DMA binding memo found]** On a **manned** experimental platform:

- Presence of crew does **not** waive COLREGs; master remains responsible.  
- Autopilot / semi-autonomy may assist but human look-out and collision-avoidance responsibility remain unless a specific permit defines otherwise.  
- Rule 2 (responsibility / good seamanship) and Rules 5–19 collision-avoidance suite remain the operational baseline for trials.  
- Danish 2017 regulatory-barrier analysis (DMA-commissioned) treats COLREGs look-out and master responsibility as core issues for autonomy levels.

**Practical implication for this project:** design trials so a competent watchkeeper can always override and fulfill Rule 5; document CONOPS and risk assessment accordingly for DEMA/DMA.

### 3.4 EU / EMSA / IMO context

**[VERIFIED]** IMO **non-mandatory MASS Code** adopted for voluntary use; **Experience-Building Phase** next; mandatory MASS Code trajectory into early 2030s (industry summaries: voluntary ~2025; mandatory entry into force often cited ~2032).  
Sources:  
- https://www.imo.org/en/mediacentre/hottopics/pages/autonomous-shipping.aspx (access 2026-07-22)  
- DNV regulatory overview: https://www.dnv.com/maritime/autonomous-remotely-operated-ships/regulatory/ (access 2026-07-22)

**[VERIFIED this session]** No standalone EMSA “sandbox permit” instrument for Danish waters was found that replaces DMA/DEMA process. EMSA role is EU-level safety/agency support; **coastal/flag administration remains the binding permit path**.

**Authorities to contact for binding answers:**

| Topic | Authority |
|---|---|
| Test framework, ship construction/equipment assessment, Future Lab | **Danish Maritime Authority** — futurelab@dma.dk ; mrj@dma.dk |
| Safety of navigation permit for autonomous/remote ops in Danish waters | **DEMA** (via DMA application process, ≥4 weeks) |
| Maritime survey permit | **Danish Geodata Agency** |
| Flag/class if Danish-flag experimental craft | DMA + recognized organization / class |

