## 4. CelesTrak SupGP

### 4.1 Current coverage (as of 2026-07-22)

**[VERIFIED]** SupGP page “Current as of **2026 Jul 22 18:16:46 UTC**” lists among others:

| Constellation / set | Source of ephemeris | Notes from live page / download |
|---|---|---|
| **Starlink** | SpaceX public repository https://api.starlink.com/public-files/ephemerides/MANIFEST.txt | SupGP CSV download this session: **~10,861 data rows** (+ header). Matching-results counter showed high unmatched count (810*) — quality flag, not absence of fleet data. Pre/post-launch stacks also published (e.g. G17-39, G17-51). |
| **OneWeb** | Space-Track, with OneWeb permission | SupGP CSV: **~651 rows**. Matching-results “1” (warn) — **not** zero-coverage; data present for large set. “Full fleet” in the sense of complete commercial constellation ephemeris: **yes as a SupGP FILE**, with residual match warnings vs GP. |
| Also: Kuiper, Planet, Iridium, GPS, GLONASS, SES, Intelsat, Telesat, Orbcomm, ISS, CSS, CPF, AST Space Mobile, EUMETSAT | Various | Iridium SupGP matching “Full Constellation: 0” (good) |

Sources:  
- https://celestrak.org/NORAD/elements/supplemental/ (fetched 2026-07-22)  
- Live CSV pulls: `sup-gp.php?FILE=starlink&FORMAT=csv`, `FILE=oneweb` (2026-07-22)

**Answer to “Starlink, OneWeb full-fleet?”:**  
- **Starlink:** SupGP covers the operational/public ephemeris set at large scale (~10k+ objects in file this day) — effectively full public ephemeris feed from SpaceX, not a partial demo.  
- **OneWeb:** SupGP file present with hundreds of objects; not empty. Residual matching warnings vs 18 SDS GP do not mean “not full fleet.”

### 4.2 Update cadence

**[VERIFIED]** CelesTrak documents that it **checks for new GP data once every 2 hours**; users should not poll faster. 18 SDS GP itself typically updates **2–3 times/day**. Starlink SupGP is regenerated from SpaceX ephemerides (SpaceX historically posts frequent ephemeris; CelesTrak fits ~first 8 h interval per literature). Page timestamp updates through the day (observed 08:15 UTC and 18:16 UTC stamps on 2026-07-22).  
Sources:  
- https://celestrak.org/NORAD/documentation/gp-data-formats.php (access 2026-07-22)  
- https://celestrak.org/NORAD/elements/supplemental/ (access 2026-07-22)

### 4.3 Access method & terms

**[VERIFIED]** Free public HTTP queries:

```
https://celestrak.org/NORAD/elements/supplemental/sup-gp.php?FILE=starlink&FORMAT=csv
https://celestrak.org/NORAD/elements/supplemental/sup-gp.php?FILE=oneweb&FORMAT=json
```

Query parameters: CATNR, INTDES, SOURCE, FILE, NAME, SPECIAL; formats TLE/2LE/XML/KVN/JSON/JSON-PRETTY/CSV (CSV default as of 2026-05-09).  
Source: https://celestrak.org/NORAD/documentation/sup-gp-queries.php (access 2026-07-22)

**[VERIFIED]** Usage policy highlights (enforceable via HTTP 403 / firewall):

- Prefer documented query APIs; only download what you need when you need it.  
- Do not poll more often than update rate (~**once per 2 hours**).  
- As of **2026-03-26**, **one-download-per-update** enforced for heavy groups (Active, Starlink GP groups); same spirit applies to bandwidth abuse.  
- Daily bandwidth abuse thresholds discussed (100–250 MB/day historical warnings).  
- Prefer **celestrak.org** not legacy .com redirects.  
- Prefer non-TLE formats for 6-digit catalog numbers (TLE exhausted for new catalog numbers ≥100000 as of 2026-07-11 notice).

Sources:  
- https://celestrak.org/usage-policy.php (access 2026-07-22)  
- https://celestrak.org/NORAD/documentation/gp-data-formats.php (access 2026-07-22)

**[ASSUMED]** For LEO-PNT research using Starlink/OneWeb as SoOP, SupGP (operator ephemeris-derived) is preferred over standard 18 SDS GP when available; still not carrier-phase ephemeris for high-precision PNT — suitable for coarse prediction / association.

